---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Nav from '../components/Nav.astro';
import Handraise from '../components/Handraise.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';

export const prerender = true;
---

<Base
  title="Vision — DVT"
  description="Why DVT exists: dashboards as declarative data, AI-native authorship, and completing the modern data stack."
>
  <Nav />
  <main>
    <!-- Page hero -->
    <section class="page-hero">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="eyebrow">Vision</div>
        <h1>Dashboards should be data.</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          The modern data stack has world-class tools for loading and transforming data.
          The visualization layer is still a GUI product. DVT changes that.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- The thesis -->
    <section class="section">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="thesis-block">
          <p class="thesis-quote">
            "Dashboards should be declarative data that AI agents and humans
            co-author — stored in a database, updated via API, where <em>every</em> visual
            property is a named, customizable parameter — not a design
            constraint imposed by the tool."
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- The problem -->
    <section class="section section-alt">
      <div class="container two-col">
        <div class="col-text">
          <h2>The gap in the modern data stack</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>dlt</strong> (Data Load Tool) extracts and loads raw data into your warehouse.
            <strong>dbt</strong> transforms and models it into analytics-ready tables.
            What comes next — visualization — has remained a solved-but-messy layer.
          </p>
          <p>
            Existing BI tools are built for point-and-click authoring. They're opaque,
            priced by seat, designed for human GUIs rather than programmatic access,
            and fundamentally incompatible with the code-native, AI-assisted workflows
            that analytics engineers already use everywhere else.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>DVT completes the trio.</strong> The right analogy is Figma or Notion,
            not dbt: dashboard specs are live data in the cloud, updated instantly via
            API or MCP — not files committed to a repo every time a chart color changes.
            The spec <em>format</em> is open and version-controlled (like dbt's model
            definition). Individual dashboards are mutable records (like a Figma file).
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="col-stack">
          <div class="stack-diagram">
            <div class="stack-row">
              <div class="stack-tool">
                <span class="tool-name">dlt</span>
                <span class="tool-role">Load</span>
              </div>
              <div class="stack-arrow">→</div>
              <div class="stack-tool">
                <span class="tool-name">dbt</span>
                <span class="tool-role">Transform</span>
              </div>
              <div class="stack-arrow">→</div>
              <div class="stack-tool dvt">
                <span class="tool-name">dvt</span>
                <span class="tool-role">Visualize</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p class="stack-label">The complete modern data stack</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Who it's for -->
    <section class="section">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>Who DVT is for</h2>
        <div class="persona-grid">
          <div class="persona-card">
            <h3>Analytics engineers &amp; data scientists</h3>
            <p>
              Already using dbt and dlt. Think in SQL. Use git. Care about reproducibility.
              Want to build dashboards programmatically — not click-and-drag. Comfortable
              with JSON specs. Would rather author a dashboard via API or let Claude write
              the spec than wrestle with a GUI.
            </p>
            <p class="persona-signal">
              "I want programmatic control over my dashboards — and the option to put them in git when it makes sense."
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="persona-card">
            <h3>Data analysts who use AI heavily</h3>
            <p>
              May not write much code, but work in environments where Claude or another agent
              drafts analytical artifacts. For this user, DVT's AI-native authoring means
              describing what they want — and an agent builds it, with every detail editable
              through a structured editor backed by the same open spec.
            </p>
            <p class="persona-signal">
              "I asked Claude to build me a revenue dashboard and it just worked."
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="persona-card">
            <h3>Platform &amp; BI teams</h3>
            <p>
              Need to standardize dashboards, enforce brand guidelines, manage permissions
              at scale, and audit what data is being shown to whom. The DAD model — dashboards
              as versioned, API-managed data — gives them auditability and control that legacy
              GUI tools cannot.
            </p>
            <p class="persona-signal">
              "We need every dashboard to be reviewable before it reaches production."
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Why now -->
    <section class="section section-alt">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>Why now</h2>
        <p class="section-lead">Three forces converge in 2025–2026 to make this tractable for a small team.</p>
        <div class="reasons">
          <div class="reason">
            <div class="reason-num">01</div>
            <div>
              <h3>LLMs can write dashboard specs</h3>
              <p>
                A well-structured JSON schema plus a good MCP server means Claude can author,
                edit, and audit dashboards as first-class operations — not just describe what
                they should look like. AI agents become first-class dashboard authors.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="reason">
            <div class="reason-num">02</div>
            <div>
              <h3>The dbt/dlt community is large and underserved</h3>
              <p>
                Analytics engineers have great tooling for the data layer and poor tooling
                for the visualization layer. They're the community most primed to adopt a
                code-native visualization tool — and they're already asking for it.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="reason">
            <div class="reason-num">03</div>
            <div>
              <h3>Apache ECharts 6 solved the rendering problem</h3>
              <p>
                A token-based theme system, dynamic switching, and deep per-element config
                APIs make a truly flexible spec-driven renderer feasible without building
                chart primitives from scratch. The hard part is done.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- The long game -->
    <section class="section">
      <div class="container long-game">
        <h2>The long game</h2>
        <p>
          DVT's long-term moat is the <strong>spec format becoming an industry standard</strong> —
          the thing every AI agent emits when building dashboards, the thing that travels
          between tools, the thing that analytics engineers put in their repos.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is the dbt playbook: the spec and CLI became the standard, and that standard —
          plus hosted Cloud, brand, and community — became the moat. The code of the engine
          is not the moat. The spec is.
        </p>
        <a href="/spec" class="btn-spec-link">See the spec →</a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <Handraise />
  </main>
  <Footer />
</Base>

<style>
  .page-hero {
    padding: var(--space-16) 0 var(--space-12);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-neutral-200);
  }

  .eyebrow {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--color-brand-mark);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }

  .page-hero h1 {
    font-size: clamp(var(--text-3xl), 5vw, 56px);
    font-weight: 800;
    line-height: 1.1;
    letter-spacing: -0.03em;
    color: var(--color-neutral-900);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-5);
    max-width: 700px;
  }

  .lead {
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    color: var(--color-neutral-600);
    line-height: 1.65;
    max-width: 600px;
  }

  .section { padding: var(--space-16) 0; }
  .section-alt {
    padding: var(--space-16) 0;
    background: var(--color-neutral-50);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-neutral-200);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-neutral-200);
  }

  .section h2 {
    font-size: var(--text-2xl);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-neutral-900);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-6);
  }

  .section-lead {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-neutral-600);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-8);
    max-width: 540px;
  }

  /* Thesis */
  .thesis-block {
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-brand-mark);
    padding-left: var(--space-8);
    max-width: 720px;
  }

  .thesis-quote {
    font-size: clamp(var(--text-lg), 2.5vw, var(--text-xl));
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--color-neutral-800);
    line-height: 1.6;
    font-style: italic;
  }

  /* Stack diagram */
  .two-col {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-16);
    align-items: center;
  }
  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .two-col { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  }

  .col-text p {
    color: var(--color-neutral-700);
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }

  .stack-diagram {
    background: var(--color-white);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-neutral-200);
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
    padding: var(--space-8);
    text-align: center;
  }

  .stack-row {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    gap: var(--space-3);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }

  .stack-tool {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 4px;
    padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-5);
    background: var(--color-neutral-100);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-neutral-200);
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
    min-width: 72px;
  }
  .stack-tool.dvt {
    background: rgba(91, 191, 186, 0.1);
    border-color: var(--color-brand-mark);
  }

  .tool-name {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-neutral-800);
  }
  .stack-tool.dvt .tool-name { color: var(--color-brand-navy); }

  .tool-role {
    font-size: 11px;
    color: var(--color-neutral-400);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
  }

  .stack-arrow { color: var(--color-neutral-300); font-size: var(--text-lg); }
  .stack-label { font-size: var(--text-xs); color: var(--color-neutral-400); }

  /* Personas */
  .persona-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(280px, 1fr));
    gap: var(--space-4);
  }

  .persona-card {
    border: 1px solid var(--color-neutral-200);
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
    padding: var(--space-6);
  }

  .persona-card h3 {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-neutral-900);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
  }

  .persona-card p {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-neutral-600);
    line-height: 1.65;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
  }

  .persona-signal {
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--color-neutral-400) !important;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-neutral-100);
    padding-top: var(--space-3);
    margin-bottom: 0 !important;
  }

  /* Why now */
  .reasons {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-8);
  }

  .reason {
    display: flex;
    gap: var(--space-6);
    align-items: flex-start;
  }

  .reason-num {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-brand-mark);
    flex-shrink: 0;
    padding-top: 3px;
    min-width: 28px;
  }

  .reason h3 {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-neutral-900);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .reason p {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-neutral-600);
    line-height: 1.65;
  }

  /* Long game */
  .long-game {
    max-width: 640px;
  }

  .long-game p {
    color: var(--color-neutral-700);
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-5);
  }

  .btn-spec-link {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-brand-navy);
    transition: color var(--transition-fast);
  }
  .btn-spec-link:hover { color: var(--color-brand-mark); }
</style>
